From: Robert Sanson <SansonR@agriquality.co.nz> [edited
Subject: Re: PRO/AH/EDR> Foot & mouth disease - UK (55)


In response to Ian Hancock's questions:

a) Direct sunlight killing of FMD virus is not directly taken into
account in the airborne spread models, however, there it is
indirectly.

1. Bright sunlight and cloud-free conditions cause unstable
atmospheric conditions due to thermals etc., hence plumes are
dispersed, causing reduced plume concentrations downwind.

2. Relative humidity below 60 percent, more likely in bright clear
conditions, is assumed to cause desiccation and death of virus.

b) Virus excretion estimation work has used experimental animals at
Pirbright (e.g., see Sellers and Parker, J. of Hygiene, Cambridge 67,
671-677, 1969) . I don't know whether these animals would be
considered "stressed." In the dispersion models, the total numbers of
animals likely to be excreting virus off the farm at the time is used.
Generally a point source representing where the animals are housed or
culled is used.

c) [In response to "To what extent are virus particles aerosolized
during disinfectant spraying, and how efficient is virus killing in
this state?, I don't know.

--
Robert Sanson, BVSc, MACVSc, PhD
